Dear Narasimha,


I have a slightly different view about the first point, t=
hough I agree to what you are saying.

1. Of course the analogy of Sun and =
Sunlight is valid, but the more interesting question remains why was there =
a clear thrust on the Sun in the spiritual literature in Gita while the ter=
minology shifted to Sunlight in Tantras. One can adopt the mystics attitude=
 and welcome, without analysing, all variations of spiritual experience. Or=
 one can adopt the philosophical-spiritual attitude and try to find a flow =
of how and why this shift happened. In India we have a solid tradition of b=
oth these two manners of treating Divine knowledge and experience. A more f=
undamental query also comes up, and which holds the key to this question (I=
MHO), is why does Sri Krishna never mention the word Kundalini in the Gita.=


2. To understand this we must start with acknowledging certain obvious fa=
cts as they come to us. The Gita (Upanishadic tradition) does not look at s=
pirituality from the fulcrum of Kundalini. Neither is it the first experien=
ce, nor a sufficient parameter for judgement. It is rather an inevitable pr=
ocess in the journey, which can happen in day one, or the very last day. By=
 itself, just by an awakening of the K shakti, one does not become spiritua=
l, neither can it be said that if one has not had an experience of the K sh=
akti yet, one is not making progress spiritually. But by the time of the Ha=
tha Yogic traditions, Nath Yogis, and Tantra, the understanding of spiritua=
lity became entirely Kundalini centric.

3. Kundalini as we read and hear o=
f it today, IMO, is insufficiently understood. The maximum that books or pe=
ople speak of is the standard diagramAtic knowledge of chakras and Shakti r=
ising up. Some correlation of this can be felt, but it is in greatest depth=
 still a mental concept and at times pretty vague and speculative. That is =
because this knowledge was passed down from capable gurus to capable discip=
les, and it needed a blind adherence to the words of a physical Guru for th=
e process of kundalinI sadhana to change a person into someone truly spirit=
ual. Hence the primacy of hanging on blindly to the Guru. The diagramtic li=
near understanding that we have of the K process has gaps, and can very oft=
en give a lopsided view of things. For example the diagram of a man sitting=
 with chakras and Shakti rising up is actual a two-dimensional representati=
on of a multidimensional phenomenon, highly prone to misunderstanding. The =
influence of each of the chakras
 pervade the whole life of a person. They =
overlap each other. Each represent psychological functions of the human org=
anism. Activating or deactiving specific petals of each chakra is important=
 and vital for sadhana of each speicifc individual, which a Guru can decide=
 accurately. The diagramatic centers only represent the focal point of that=
 range of pyschological functions, but the sphere of influence of each chak=
ra can permeate into the whole system and consequently into life in general=
. It is impossible for any sadhaka to navigate the path, with a K centric v=
iew of spirituality, unless guided constantly by a physical guru of great d=
epth, knowledge and wisdom abouit Kundalini Yoga. Otherwise, like Columbus,=
 one will start for India and end up reaching America.

4. The concept of G=
uru and Shishya was always there, but in the Gita and Upanishads, Guru was =
the Guru tattwa, which can manifest from an individual, or through anything=
 provided the disciple is ready. Like Dattatreya had 24 non-human gurus. Bu=
t this kind of concept of Guru is impractical when it comes to Kundalini Yo=
ga. One can become genuinely spiritual by contemplating and trying to imbib=
e the advice of Krishna in the Gita without a physical Guru. Same cannot be=
 done in Kundalini centric view of sadhana.

5. In the Gita tradition, or f=
or that matter any spiritual tradition, Kundalini will awaken for sure, but=
 since spirituality is not looked at from that prism, therefore this proces=
s is left to Nature to happen on its own, when a sadhaka is ready internall=
y. Moreover, the judgement of spirituality - whether a person is spiritual =
or non-spiritual - cannot be made based merely on an experience of Kundalin=
i itself. Until the K shakti rises up to meet the higher spiritual realms a=
nd brings down those energies into life, and then those energies settle dow=
n into the system, actual spiritual effects may not be visible.

6. The Kun=
dalini is the force of the pranamayakosha which holds the external personal=
ity together. The aim is to liberate it from its mundane function and make =
it shoot-up to purify itself. Every time it comes into contact with the hig=
her planes, it imbibes the energies and bring them down into life. The pran=
amayakosha is pure shakti, constantly in motion. This is a tremendous force=
. Because Force in its original nature is the domain of the Mother, the dyn=
amic aspect of Sat-Chit-Ananda, therefore Kundalini is called Shakti sadhan=
a or Mother Kundalini.

7. In the light of the above points, it can be fair=
ly understood why the Gita puts its trust on Purushottama, while the Tantra=
s - whose spiritual prism was Kundalini centric - puts the focus on Adya Sh=
akti.

8. In this age when Guurus are rare, genuine paramparas are rarer st=
ill, and capable sadhaks are negligible, a Kundalini centric view of sadhan=
a can be detrimental for most people.

9. Of course, these are my view-poin=
t as I see it. Feel free to disagree.

